0.1 Introduction

  • Monocle introduced the strategy of using RNA-Seq for single-cell trajectory analysis. Rather than purifying cells into discrete states experimentally, Monocle uses an algorithm to learn the sequence of gene expression changes each cell must go through as part of a dynamic biological process. Once it has learned the overall trajectory of gene expression changes, Monocle can place each cell at its proper position in the trajectory.

  • If there are multiple outcomes for the process, Monocle will reconstruct a branched trajectory. These branches correspond to cellular decisions, and Monocle provides powerful tools for identifying the genes affected by them and involved in making them.

In this tutorial which is based on the official vignette of the Monocle3 which is available at Trapnell lab. We will use the dataset

0.2.3 Required Libraries and Path set ups

To save verbose from various libries we will use the suppressPackageStartupMessages(), this suppress the all the package start calls.

suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(SeuratDisk))
suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(Seurat))
suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(monocle3))
suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(tidyverse))
suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(ggplot2)) # For Plotting
suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(wesanderson)) # For Coloring
suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(DT)) # Dynamic tables

We will also set paths for input and out data for easir I/O. We are using absolute paths to avoid any conflicts .Throughout the analysis we will save all the data in the native .RDS format which is a native format for R.

# Parent directories
inPath = "/home/esr/HandsOn5_A_Monocle3_Trajectory_Analysis/input_data"
outPath = "/home/esr/HandsOn5_A_Monocle3_Trajectory_Analysis/output_data"

# We will also make a few other empty directoires in the outpout folder
imgPath = paste(inPath, "images", sep = "/")
tabPath = paste(inPath, "tables", sep = "/")
rdsPath = paste(inPath, "rObjects", sep = "/")

0.3.2 Creation of cell_data_set object for Monocle3

  • CDS aka cell_data_set, is the S4 which is used by the Monocle3. It inherits all the slots of the SingleCellExperiment Class. Additinally it stores information about the principal graph and, trajectory etc.
  • Just like the SingleCellExperiment, the cell_data_set also requires the following,

    1. Count Table: We can extract it from the seurat object. Ideally this has to be supplied in the dgCMatrix class.

    2. Cell Metadata: This is a R dataframe, where the rownames correspond to the columns of the counts and the columns contain information about the cells. Such as exprimental capture time or cell type annotation labels in our case.

    3. Gene Metadata: This is also a R dataframe, where the rownames correspond to the rows of the counts and the columns contain information about the genes Such as gene functions, symbols or ontologies etc. Also, this dataframe should have a column by the name of gene_short_name, which is later used in plotting fucntion of the Monocle3.

Lets do it one by one and inspect the data. We start with the rawCounst, dont worry we will later also show you how to do the analysis with normalized data.

# Extract the Raw counts
rawCounts <- sob.sub@assays$RNA@counts

# View a few line of data
datatable(as.data.frame(rawCounts[c(1:20),c(1:20)]))

Now we extract the cell level metadata. We will also plot how much of each cell type we have. We make the plots using the finer resolution hiereachy of teh cell types.

# Extract the Raw counts
cellMetaData <- sob.sub@meta.data

# View a few line of data
datatable(cellMetaData)
# Plot  of cell types
cellMetaData %>%
  group_by(predicted.celltype.l2) %>%
  summarise(count = n()) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=predicted.celltype.l2, y=count, fill=predicted.celltype.l2)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity") + #scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set3")+
  labs(x="Cell Types", y="Number of Cells", title="Counts of annoated Cell types") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1, vjust = 0.5)) +
  theme_minimal()
